          "body": "The psalm ends with one of the most beautiful lines in the Psalter: 'So that I may walk before God in the light of the living' (56:13). Deliverance from death and stumbling is not the final goal — it is the means to an end. The end is *halakh* (walking) before God's *paneh* (face) in the *or* (light) of the *chay* (the living). This is covenant fellowship language — to walk before God is to live in His conscious presence, accountable and known (Genesis 17:1; 1 Kings 3:6). The 'light of the living' contrasts with the darkness of Sheol, the realm of death the enemies threatened. David has been pulled from death's shadow into the realm where life is lived before God's face. The whole psalm — fear, trust, tears, vow — has been moving toward this: not merely survival, but the renewed ability to inhabit the covenant life God intends for those He rescues."
