        "body": "The refrain from verse 4 returns in verses 10-11, but with a structurally significant addition. In verse 4, the refrain named only *Elohim* (God). In verse 10, the refrain names both *Elohim* and *Yehovah* — the covenant name of God, the LORD who appeared to Moses in the burning bush (Exodus 3:14-15), who bound Himself to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and who cannot break His own promise. The covenant name appears exactly once in the psalm, here in the doubled refrain that follows the knowledge-claim of verse 9.\n\nThe word being praised is *davar* — the same word the enemies were distorting in verse 5. There, *davar* was twisted against David; here, *davar* is the object of David's *halal* (boasting praise). The contrast is precise: the enemies' speech destroys; God's word saves. The reason David can praise God's word is that the word has proven reliable — it has not shifted with circumstances or buckled under the weight of David's exile.\n\nVerse 11 completes the refrain: 'In God I have put my trust, I shall not be afraid. What can man do to me?' The second occurrence of the rhetorical question uses *adam* (man as human being) where verse 4 used *basar* (man as mere flesh). The two words overlap in meaning but *adam* carries the additional nuance of the creature as opposed to the Creator, humanity in its finitude. The question remains rhetorical — the answer remains 'nothing ultimate.' But the second asking of the question carries more weight than the first because it comes after the knowledge-claim of verse 9. David is not asserting this fearlessness by an act of will alone; he is asserting it from a position of demonstrated knowledge.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yehovah* — the covenant personal name of Israel's God, appearing only here in the psalm; its appearance in the doubled refrain is not accidental. *Halal* (praise) — to boast, to shine, to make noise about; the word carries the connotation of public declaration. *Adam* (man) — the creature of Genesis 2, formed from the dust; the name carries its own limitation within it."
